Supplementary material

Research strategy

A systematic literature search was performed on December 9th, 2019 in Medline and Web of Science databases according to the following search strategy MEDLINE: myoid[All Fields] AND (testicular neoplasms[MeSH Terms] OR (testicular[All Fields] AND neoplasms[All Fields]) OR testicular neoplasms[All Fields] OR (tumor[All Fields] AND testis[All Fields]) OR tumor testis[All Fields]) Web of Science: TOPIC: (myoid tumor testis). Timespan: All years. Indexes: SCI-EXPANDED, SSCI, A&HCI, CPCI-S, CPCI-SSH, ESCI

Search strategy flow chart

Age model

Prior predictive simulations

We modeled age \(A_i\) as normally distributed, with mean \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\). \[A_i \sim Normal( \mu, \sigma)\] We looked for a prior distribution with a mean compatible with human age. We simulated several normal distribution:

Prior predictive simulation for age. The vertical lines indicate 0 and 120 years.

For \(\mu\) we chose a \(Normal(60, 20)\) that put most of the mass of the mean in the a plausible range. We chose a \(Exponential(1)\) prior for the standard deviation \(\sigma\) for maximum entropy reason.

Model coefficients

Inference for Stan model: 4 chains, each with iter=1000; warmup=500; thin=1;post-warmup draws per chain=500, total post-warmup draws=2000.

Parameter mean sd 5.5% 94.5% n_eff \(\hat{R}\)
\(\mu\) 37.87 2.82 33.45 42.39 1047 1
\(\sigma\) 11.39 1.45 9.35 13.90 1194 1

Samples were drawn using NUTS. For each parameter, n_eff is a crude measure of effective sample size, and \(\hat{R}\) is the potential scale reduction factor on split chains (at convergence, \(\hat{R}\)=1).

Size Model

Prior predictive simulations

Similarly, we modeled size \(S_i\) as normally distributed, with mean \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\). \[S_i \sim Normal( \mu, \sigma)\] Again with prior predictive simulation we looked for a prior distribution with a mean compatible with the meaning of size (i.e.most of the mass would not be non-negative). We simulated several normal distribution:

Prior predictive simulation for size. The vertical lines indicate 0 cm.

For \(\mu\) we chose a \(Normal(5, 0.75)\) that put most of the mass of the mean in the a plausible range. We chose a \(Exponential(1)\) prior for the standard deviation \(\sigma\) for maximum entropy reason.

Model coefficients

Inference for Stan model: 4 chains, each with iter=1000; warmup=500; thin=1;post-warmup draws per chain=500, total post-warmup draws=2000.

Parameter mean sd 5.5% 94.5% n_eff \(\hat{R}\)
\(\mu\) 2.82 0.33 2.35 3.39 809 1.01
\(\sigma\) 1.32 0.28 0.96 1.82 731 1.01

Mitosis Model

Prior predictive simulations

Similarly, we modeled size \(M_i\) as zero inflated Poisson (ZIPoisson) with rate \(\lambda\); the zero inflated Poisson is a type of model that is used in ecology: \[\begin{equation} M_i \sim ZIPoisson(p_i, \lambda_i)\\ logit(p_i) = \alpha_p\\ log(\lambda_i) = \alpha_\lambda\\ \alpha_p \sim Normal(-1.5, 1)\\ \alpha_\lambda \sim Normal(0.5, 0.5) \end{equation}\]

Prior predictive simulation for mitotis.

We chose as a prior for \(\alpha_p\) a \(Normal(-1.5, 1)\), since we expeted more often than not to see mitosis; on the other hand we chose \(Normal(0.5, 0.5)\) for \(\alpha_\lambda\) since we exected a low mitotic activity.

Model coefficients

Inference for Stan model: 4 chains, each with iter=1000; warmup=500; thin=1;post-warmup draws per chain=500, total post-warmup draws=2000.

Parameter mean sd 5.5% 94.5% n_eff \(\hat{R}\)
\(\alpha_p\) -0.38 0.56 -1.28 0.45 1155 1
\(\alpha_\lambda\) 1.08 0.22 0.72 1.42 1083 1
